shared_text:
Parrish Elementary School Tornadoes
August 9 at 11:47 AM ¬∑

PEMS News Release

The Parrish Elementary/Middle School administration, faculty, and staff are proud to announce that PEMS has been awarded the 21st Century Learning Grant. The 21st Century Grant is awarded by the Alabama State Department of Education - Montgomery and the U.S. Department of Education - Washington, D.C.

The 21st Century Grant will allow PEMS to offer an after school/virtual program (following the Alabama Department of Public Health Covid -19 guidelines) starting October 2020. The 21st Century Grant will allow PEMS to offer afterschool instruction/tutoring by certified teachers as well as other educational services. Also, this grant will allow PEMS to offer a summer program (summer 2021).

More details will come in the near future.

Go Tornadoes!

Shawna McCullar
June 11 at 2:55 PM ¬∑

Congratulations to Kendall Watkins (Cordova), Josh Smith (Dora), and Chris Stillwell (Dora) for passing your state boards and becoming Certified IBEW Electrical Journeymen, and thanks to Instructor Mark Palmer for getting them there! They will be making around $30 an hour with full benefits. This required 8000 hours under a master electrician or an electrical engineer, 1000 hours of post-secondary training at the IBEW Apprenticeship School, and 54 credit hours recognized by UA and AL community colleges (ALL AT NO COST!!) One of his students made 69,500 last year as only an apprentice. Mark Palmer has placed 15-20 students there in the last 6 years (including Hispanic, Black, and female students). One of the the IBEW instructors told me that if Mark recommended someone, he didn‚Äôt have to ask questions. The electrical technology program at the WCCT is the reigning Construction Wiring Champion in the state of AL. We are so proud of you all and thank you for paving the way for our other students to have this amazing opportunity. IBEW L.U 103 WCCT Mark Palmer

post_text:
Walker County has been approved for Baylor University's Emergency Meals-to-You program! It is a partnership between our district, the U.S. Department of Agriculture, and Baylor University. This program is for households whose student(s) receive free or reduced priced meals. Enrollment is open now and will remain open until 4 pm May 26, 2020. This is a strict enrollment period. Meal kits containing shelf-stable food will be mailed directly to the qualifying homes during the month of June.

Parents must sign up online at the following link: https://mealstoyou.org/emergency-meals-to-you-application/

Link to instructional video: https://baylor.app.box.com/s/2h206bp0rqu7lqmt2xomgmhlpz7jdmso/file/656003578780

Joel Hagood
May 19 at 10:09 PM ¬∑

FIRST CLASS PRE-K: I am proud to announce the Walker County School System has been awarded 4 additional First Class Pre-K classrooms by the Alabama Department of Early Childhood Education. This brings our total FIRST CLASS PRE-K classrooms in the Walker County School System to 14. The following schools received the additional sites: Cordova, Curry, Oakman, and Valley.

This is a competitive process with only 55 units awarded statewide, and 4 of those were awarded to our system. Thank you to Senator Greg Reed and Representatives Connie Rowe and Tim Wadsworth for your efforts and support. We will be pursuing additional units this summer.

post_text:
Latest statement from Dr. Hagood

Please note given the Governor‚Äôs recent ‚ÄúStay at Home‚Äù order it is now necessary for us to adjust our original plan for packet pickups at our respective schools for those lacking Online access and/or appropriate devices.

Packets will now include assignments for the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year instead of week-to-week assignments. Principals will provide more specific information concerning his/her respective school soon. Packets will be available for pick-up at your school on Thursday, April 9th. Nurses will also be present at your respective schools on this day from 8 a.m. until 12 noon for medication pick-up for those who have medication still at school as a result of our required closure.

I appreciate your patience and understanding as we all continue to adapt and adjust to these unprecedented times in our lives. God Bless! Stay safe! And stay healthy!

post_text: In an abundance of caution, Governor Kay Ivey has declared a state of emergency for the state of Alabama. All K-12 schools in the state will close for two weeks starting Thursday, March 19 to prevent the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19). The expected date of return for students is April 6th. There will be no athletic practices, extracurricular activities or games during that time. Each school principal will have information on optional learning opportunities for students before school closes next Wednesday. We will keep you updated as information becomes available.

post_text:
Good evening! I understand concerns, probably more than anyone when it comes to student safety, considering I am responsible for more than 7,000 students in the Walker County School System. This number includes my own two children. Today‚Äôs event was a generic threat, and NOT specific to any one location. Based on the information we had we took the necessary measures outlined in our safety plan. This event called for SECURE PERIMETER and HEIGHTENED AWARENESS.

It is not our practice to do a ‚Äúcallout‚Äù to parents, or post on social media, during these type of events. This creates chaos and confusion and most often will interfere with our most important task, which is protecting our children. Please know we always communicate with you at the appropriate time when these events occur. Each school has a safety plan that is well thought out, communicated among staff, and practiced. We work directly with law enforcement and community agencies when these events arise.

Thank you and God Bless!
Dr. Joel Hagood
Superintendent
Walker County Schools

post_text: The West Alabama Consortium (Winfield City, Haleyville City, Marion County, Lamar County, Fayette County, Jasper City, Walker County, and Bibb County) rolled out the red carpet for our child nutrition professionals on Tuesday, July 31st as we hosted the 1st Annual Regional CNP In-Service! Our workers were treated to a star-studded line up of speakers including the fabulous Maureen G. Mulvaney (MGM), Phyliss Fenn (ADPH), Brent Morrison (Encompass Health) and Heather McDermott (Alabaster City). Our staff members were treated to a day filled with VIP swag bags, a Lunch n' Learn session, a visit from local SNAP-Ed agents from the Alabama Cooperative Extension System and a fun photo booth! Our #CNPsuperstars are better, stronger, together!
